    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1874-01-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1874-01-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="317" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d317">
                <head>No. 315.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">Edward
                                Thornton</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1874-01-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">January</hi> 24, 1874</date>.
                            (Received January 28.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to my note of yesterday’s date
                        upon the subject of the coolie trade, I have the honor to inform you that I
                        have this day received a dispatch from Earl Granville, in which he states
                        that a telegram has been received from Her Majesty’s consul at Canton to the
                        effect that a proclamation has been issued by the governor of Macao,
                        ordering the cessation, within three months, of cooly-emigration from that
                        port.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>EDW’D THORNTON.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
